\f0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 1. 
\f1\fs26 \cb1 \strokec5 Response-variable definition\

\f0\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The response variables predicted in this study are the concentrations of 
\f2\b particulate inorganic carbon (PIC)
\f0\b0  and 
\f2\b particulate organic carbon (POC)
\f0\b0 .\cb1 \
\cb3 Regarding the modeling approach:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Transformation:
\f0\b0  The researchers modeled 
\f2\b log10-transformed values
\f0\b0  of these concentrations. This is evident in the variable importance plots and the partial dependence sensitivity analyses, which were both conducted on the log10 transformed target data sets.\cb1 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Modeling Task:
\f0\b0  The study utilized 
\f2\b regression
\f0\b0  only. The importance of environmental predictors was quantified using 
\f2\b root mean squared error (RMSE)
\f0\b0 , which is a standard metric for regression tasks. While the text notes that Random Forests can be used for both classification and regression, the specific application here was to uncover nonlinear relationships and predict continuous concentration values
\fs28 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\cf2 2. 
\f1\fs26 \cb1 \strokec5 Predictor set\cf5 \

\f0\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The study utilized a set of 
\f2\b 11 environmental variables
\f0\b0  as predictors for the random forest models.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 Full List of Environmental Variables and Sourcing\cf4 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The predictors were sourced from several established oceanographic and atmospheric data sets:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Temperature, Salinity, Mixed Layer Depth (MLD), Silicate, Phosphate, and Nitrate:
\f0\b0  These were obtained from the 
\f2\b World Ocean Atlas 2018
\f0\b0  data set.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Vertical Velocity:
\f0\b0  Acquired from the 
\f2\b ECCO
\f0\b0  (Estimating the Circulation and Climate of the Ocean) reanalysis data set, version 4 release 4.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Net Shortwave Radiation (Light):
\f0\b0  Sourced from the 
\f2\b International Satellite Cloud Climatology Project
\f0\b0  via the 
\f2\b Objectively Analyzed Air\uc0\u8208 Sea Fluxes (OAFlux)
\f0\b0  Project.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 pCO2:
\f0\b0  Obtained from the 
\f2\b MPI\uc0\u8208 ULB\u8208 SOMFFN
\f0\b0  globally interpolated climatological product.\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Dissolved Iron and Ammonium:
\f0\b0  Because no globally interpolated observational data sets exist for these sparsely sampled variables, the researchers used 
\f2\b synthetic \'93observational\'94 data sets
\f0\b0  generated from the ensemble average of 
\f2\b CMIP6 Earth System Models (ESMs)
\f0\b0 .
\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Temporal and Spatial Resolution\cf4 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Spatial Resolution:
\f0\b0  All predictors were aligned to a 
\f2\b 1\'b0 grid
\f0\b0 . Satellite target data (originally 9 km) were regridded to this 1\'b0 resolution to match the observed predictor data sets.\cb1 \
\ls3\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Temporal Resolution:
\f0\b0  The variables were 
\f2\b monthly averaged
\f0\b0  or provided as 
\f2\b monthly climatologies
\f0\b0 . For example, the PIC and POC target data spanned a monthly climatology from July 2002 to December 2022.
\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Nature of the Variables\cf4 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The variables used in the model were primarily 
\f2\b surface-based or climatological
\f0\b0 , rather than instantaneous:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Surface-only:
\f0\b0  Net shortwave radiation was measured at the ocean surface. pCO2 and most nutrient/temperature data represent surface or near-surface conditions.\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Depth-specific:
\f0\b0  Vertical velocity was specifically acquired for a 
\f2\b depth of 55 m
\f0\b0 .\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Climatological/Averaged:
\f0\b0  All predictors were 
\f2\b monthly averages or climatologies
\f0\b0 . The study did not use instantaneous measurements, as the goal was to link large-scale spatiotemporal distributions of carbon to environmental drivers.\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Mixed Layer:
\f0\b0  Mixed layer depth was included as a specific predictor to account for how it modulates both light supply and grazing pressure\cb1 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 3. data match up method\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The study aligned observations with environmental fields using the following data matchup methods:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Alignment and Spatial Interpolation:
\f0\b0  To ensure consistency across all data sets, the satellite-derived target data (PIC and POC), which had an original spatial resolution of 9 km, were 
\f2\b regridded to a 1\'b0 spatial resolution
\f0\b0 . This alignment was achieved by 
\f2\b taking the mean of all observed points within each 1\'b0 square
\f0\b0 . This process smoothed out small-scale variability, such as eddies, and matched the resolution of the objectively analyzed environmental predictor data sets.\cb1 \
\ls5\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Temporal Windowing:
\f0\b0  The researchers utilized 
\f2\b monthly averaged data and monthly climatologies
\f0\b0 . The target data sets were based on a monthly climatology spanning from July 2002 to December 2022. Predictors were similarly sourced as monthly averages or globally interpolated climatological products to match this temporal scale.\cb1 \
\ls5\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Handling Missing Data:
\f0\b0  The study employed specific strategies for variables or regions with missing information:\cb1 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Synthetic Predictors:
\f0\b0  Because globally interpolated observational data sets do not exist for dissolved iron and ammonium, the researchers used 
\f2\b synthetic \'93observational\'94 data sets
\f0\b0  generated from the ensemble average of CMIP6 Earth System Models (ESMs).\cb1 \
\ls5\ilvl1
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Gap-Filling in Target Data:
\f0\b0  To address analytical gaps in low-light regions (such as high latitudes during winter) where satellite data is often missing, they 
\f2\b replaced missing months at points with some existing measurements using the 1st percentile value
\f0\b0  of the corresponding global data set. This allowed the model to account for regions where phytoplankton persist in a dormant or low-biomass state.
\fs28 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 4. filtering and QC\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 The study applied the following filtering and quality control (QC) measures to the data sets:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Geographic Domain Restrictions:
\f0\b0  The study utilized 
\f2\b global ocean
\f0\b0  data sets,. While no specific latitudes were explicitly excluded, the researchers noted "analytical gaps" in 
\f2\b high-latitude regions during the winter
\f0\b0  because passive satellite products lack information in these low-light areas.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Seasonal Handling and Filtering:
\f0\b0  No seasons were filtered out. Instead, to address the missing data in low-light regions (like high-latitude winters), the researchers 
\f2\b replaced missing months
\f0\b0  at coordinates that had at least some existing measurements with the 
\f2\b 1st percentile value
\f0\b0  of the corresponding global data set. This allowed the model to represent the "dormant state" of phytoplankton in these conditions.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Quality Flags and Outlier Management:
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\tx940\tx1440\pardeftab720\li1440\fi-1440\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl1\cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 The primary method for handling data quality and "dropouts" (such as those caused by clouds) was 
\f2\b spatial regridding
\f0\b0 . By averaging all 9-km observed points into 1\'b0 grid cells, the researchers 
\f2\b eliminated most cloud-related dropouts
\f0\b0  and smoothed out small-scale noise from eddies.\cb1 \
\ls6\ilvl1\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u9702 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 The authors acknowledged potential biases in satellite algorithms, such as those caused by high chlorophyll concentrations, sediments, or the PIC "package effect," but chose to use these products to maintain 
\f2\b global measurement consistency
\f0\b0  and provide a large enough data set for machine learning.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Minimum Data Thresholds:
\f0\b0  For the gap-filling procedure in low-light regions, a threshold was implied: missing values were only filled for grid points that had 
\f2\b "some measurements"
\f0\b0  existing in the original PIC and POC data sets. This ensured that the model only predicted for areas known to have some level of carbon presence rather than attempting to fill completely data-void regions.
\fs28 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf4 \strokec4 \
5. sampling design \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf4 \cb3 Jin et al. (2024)\cf4 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Total Sample Size:
\f0\b0  The study utilized a 
\f2\b monthly climatology
\f0\b0  spanning 20 years (July 2002 to December 2022). While the exact count of data points is not explicitly totaled, the data set covers the global ocean regridded to a 
\f2\b 1\'b0 spatial resolution
\f0\b0 . A full 1\'b0 global grid contains 64,800 cells per month, and the authors note the resulting data set was large enough for tree-based machine learning.\cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Spatial Clustering:
\f0\b0  Observations were initially high-resolution (9 km) but were 
\f2\b regridded to a uniform 1\'b0 grid
\f0\b0 . This process smoothed out small-scale variability, such as eddies, and ensured that the target data aligned with the resolution of the global environmental predictor data sets.\cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Thinning/Weighting:
\f0\b0  To reduce the impact of oversampling or "dropouts" (such as those caused by cloud cover in satellite data), the researchers 
\f2\b took the mean of all observed 9-km points within each 1\'b0 square
\f0\b0 . This effectively thinned the dense satellite observations into a consistent, lower-resolution global product.\cb1 \
\ls7\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Repeated Measurements:
\f0\b0  The study addressed repeated measurements over time by creating a 
\f2\b monthly climatology
\f0\b0 . This means all observations for a specific month across the 20-year period were averaged into a single representative monthly value for each grid cell.
\fs28 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs24 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 Dunne et al. (2005)\cf4 \cb1 \strokec4 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa120\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf4 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Total Sample Size:
\f0\b0  This study compiled a synthesis of field observations from approximately 40 oceanographic studies, resulting in 
\f2\b 122 independent observations
\f0\b0  of ecosystem state. A subset of 
\f2\b 39 sites
\f0\b0  was used for analyses requiring specific ecosystem size structure data.\cb1 \
\ls8\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Spatial Clustering:
\f0\b0  The authors noted that some sampling was 
\f2\b performed intensively at single locations
\f0\b0  rather than being geographically or temporally random.\cb1 \
\ls8\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Thinning/Weighting:
\f0\b0  To prevent oversampling in dense regions from biasing the results, the researchers 
\f2\b grouped ecologically similar conditions
\f0\b0 . This was done to "preserve the natural variability... without excessively weighting individual locations".\cb1 \
\ls8\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Repeated Measurements:
\f0\b0  For intensive sampling at single sites, data were grouped to ensure they did not disproportionately influence the global model. Additionally, to handle temporal variability and ensure compatibility between different measurement types, the study assumed a 
\f2\b steady-state condition
\f0\b0  or explicitly accounted for documented biomass accumulation as part of export production.
\fs28 \
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\sa120\partightenfactor0

