\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Split vs. Calibration:
\f0\b0  This study focuses on calibrating empirical and mechanistic models rather than a modern machine learning train/test split. The authors used the full global data compilation to determine the most significant environmental correlates and establish model benchmarks.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Handling Spatially Clustered Data:
\f0\b0  To account for observations that were 
\f2\b spatially clustered
\f0\b0  (intensive sampling at single locations), the researchers 
\f2\b grouped ecologically similar conditions
\f0\b0 . This was done to preserve natural variability without allowing individual, heavily sampled locations to excessively weight the statistical results.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Validation through Bootstrapping:
\f0\b0  Instead of k-fold cross-validation, the study employed 
\f2\b bootstrapping
\f0\b0  for parameter estimation. Specifically, the data set was 
\f2\b resampled 10,000 times with replacement
\f0\b0  to calculate the most likely parameter values and their 95% confidence intervals.\cb1 \
\ls10\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec4 Temporal Considerations:
\f0\b0  For non-steady state conditions, the authors explicitly accounted for 
\f2\b biomass accumulation or depletion
\f0\b0  as part of export production to maximize compatibility between different data types (e.g., f-ratio vs. pe-ratio estimates).
\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 \strokec4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

