\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Key Methodological Guardrails\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Even though the data structures differ, Dunne's methodology provides a "guardrail" for your project regarding 
\f2\b spatial autocorrelation
\f0\b0 :\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls22\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Handling Oversampling:
\f0\b0  Because your Arctic data is spatially and temporally autocorrelated, you should adopt a strategy similar to Dunne\'92s 
\f2\b grouping of ecologically similar conditions
\f0\b0 . This prevents dense sampling regions from over-weighting the model\'97a risk you have already identified as needing mitigation through 
\f2\b temporal block train/test splits
\f0\b0  rather than random row splits.\
\ls22\ilvl0
\f2\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Comparison to Jin et al. (2024):
